Exploring the Wharton Data

Objectives

1.Proportion of men to women within firm 2.Proportion of white to non-white 3. Within race: we want to look at tenure (group_by industries)

References:

  1. Metadata explanation: https://wrds-web.wharton.upenn.edu/wrds/ds/riskmetrics/rmdirectors/index.cfm?navId=245

wharton <-read.csv('wharton/select_data.csv')
sp500 <- read.csv('s&p500/sp500.csv')
#Renaming
colnames(sp500)[colnames(sp500)=="Symbol"] <- "ticker"

#Remove Unnecessary Columns
sp500 <- select (sp500,-c(SEC.Filings,HQ.Location))

#Merge
data <- merge(wharton, sp500, by = "ticker")
#Lets now explore this ungrouped, barely filtered data with DataExplorer
introduce(data)
plot_intro(data)

#Are we missing anything?
plot_missing(data)

This tells me I want to be looking at the last 3 columns: RT_ID, Pcnt_Ctrl_VotingPower, Year_of_termination so that they dont mess up our data exploration. It seems as if the Pcnt_Ctrl_VotingPower is an incredibly sparse column and Im doubtful of the reliability of the value when it says NA.

#Lets remove the RT_ID from wharton and year_of_termination, then re-merge
wharton <- select(wharton, -c(RT_ID, Year_of_termination))
data <- merge(wharton, sp500, by = "ticker")
plot_missing(data)

Unfortunately, it seems as if the votingpower variable has the most missing data. This is unfortunate because voting power may be a good variable to describe status. Lets drop the column for now and continue to our analysis grouped by industry.

wharton <- select(wharton, -c(Pcnt_Ctrl_Votingpower))
data <- merge(wharton, sp500, by = "ticker")
plot_missing(data)

industry_freq <- as.data.frame(table(data$GIC.Sector))
#Recoding the Female, OWNLESS1
data <- data %>% 
  mutate(female = ifelse(female == "Yes", 1, 0)) %>%
  mutate(OWNLESS1 = ifelse(OWNLESS1 == "Yes", 1, 0))

create_report(data)
